Anonymous Tue 27 Jul 2021 01:39:27 No.40468530 Report
Quoted By:
>>40468001
It depends on the genre.
A conversation should do at least one of the following: reveal new information, refine previous information, raise the stakes/tension, or create/modify conflict.
So...
>"Did you know Anon hooked up with Waifur last night?"
>"Is that why he blew off human co-worker girl at work yesterday? Ouch."
>"The blonde one? OMG, if she finds out then Anon's in for it."
>"Tell me about it. I heard she just moved into HR, and Anon's performance review is later this week."

Watching movies with sharp dialogue can be a good way to refine how you think about structure, and I've written some very concise conversations in longer pieces. If you've got the emotion down, 1-3 sentences is all it takes to deliver the wham line that covers one of the four tasks above. On the other hand, sometimes the conversation (which is only happening once because it's a shorter story) is the core piece of those 5k words.
